r. There is concern that the shale, which separates the\ncarbonate and sandstone aquifers�sand and pyritic oolite itself contains\nsulphides�will, when exposed to injected air from the CanWhite Sands extraction\nprocess, turn to acid. ","index":"00415","speaker":""},{"html":"����� An\nadditional concern with the proposed mine and plant is the potential to pollute\nthe Brokenhead River and the aquatic food chain leading to Lake Winnipeg. ","index":"00416","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Residents in the area have also expressed fears of being\noverexposed to silica dust during production, as there has been a demonstrated\nlack of safety and environmental procedures by the CanWhite Sands Corporation\nduring the exploratory drilling phase. Signage and fencing has been poor;\nidentifying and required mine claim tags were missing; there were no warnings\nfor silica dust exposure and no coverings to prevent exposure of the silica\nstockpiles to the elements.","index":"00417","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Residents'\nconcerns, including the fact that boreholes which should have been promptly and\nproperly sealed were left open for a year. The drilling of hundreds of\nimproperly sealed boreholes yearly creates significant risks of surface\ncontamination, mixing of aquifer waters and drainage of surface fecal matters\ninto the aquifer. ","index":"00418","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>*</b>\n(15:10)","index":"00419","speaker":""},{"html":"����� There\nis also a risk of subsidence around each borehole as a result of sand\nextraction.","index":"00420","speaker":""},{"html":"����� There are also potential transboundary issues that need to be\naddressed as the aquifers extend into Minnesota. ","index":"00421","speaker":""},{"html":"����� This project should not proceed, as no licensing conditions and\nmitigation measures will alleviate the risk to all Manitobans and the\nenvironment since CanWhite Sands Corporation plans to use an unprece�dented\nmining technique with no established safe out�come. The corporation has gone on\nrecord indicating that it does not know how to mine for the silica in the water\nsupply and need to develop a new extraction meth�odology that has never been\ndone before.","index":"00422","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Contamination of the aquifers and the environ�ment is irreversible\nand there are many surface sources of high purity silica that can be extracted\nwith�out endangering two essential regional aquifers. ","index":"00423","speaker":""},{"html":"����� We petition the Legislative Assembly of Manitoba as follows:","index":"00424","speaker":""},{"html":"����� (1) To urge the provincial government to undertake a combined\nreview of the Vivian Sand Facility processing plant and the mining/extraction\nportion of the operation as a class 3 development with&nbsp;&nbsp;a review by\nManitoba's Clean Environment Commission to include public hearings and partici�pant\nfunding.","index":"00425","speaker":""},{"html":"����� (2) To urge the provincial government to halt all activity at the\nmine and plant until the Clean Environment Commission's review is completed and\nthe project proposal has been thoroughly evaluated.","index":"00426","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Signed by Kelly Shields, Rob Miller, Gerald Choudant <i>[phonetic]</i>\nand many, many others. ","index":"00427","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nDeputy Speaker:</b> In accordance with rule 133-6, when petitions are read they\nmust be deemed to be received by the House. ","index":"00428","speaker":""},{"html":"����� The\nhonourable member for Elmwood.","index":"00429","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Can\nthe member from Elmwood unmute his mic? Or turn on his video, too? ","index":"00430","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr. Jim\nMaloway (Elmwood):</b> I have. ","index":"00431","speaker":"Jim Maloway"},{"html":"<b><span style=\"display:none\">&nbsp;</span></b>","index":"00432","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nDeputy Speaker:</b> Okay. The video�we can't see you on the video. ","index"